Reduce the problem \SUBSETSUM to the problem \PARTITION and prove that \PARTITION belongs to \NP.








PARTITION



Given a set of integers S (possibly with repetitions), determine whether S can be partitioned into two subsets S_1 and S_2 (i.e., each element of S belongs either to S_1 or to S_2, but not the two at the same time) such that 
\sum_{x\in S_1} x = \sum_{x\in S_2}x\ .












SUBSETSUM



Given a set of integers S (possibly with repetitions) and an integer k, determine whether there exists a subset A\subseteq S such that

\sum_{x\in A} x = k\ .

Analyze the cost of the following recursive functions.
They all compute x^n for n \in \mathbb N in different ways.
double power_1 (double x, int n) { 
    if (n == 0){
        return 1;
    } 
    else {
        return x*power_1(x, n - 1); 
    }
}
double power_2 (double x, int n) { 
    if (n == 0){
        return 1;
    } else if (n % 2 == 0) {
        int y = power_2(x, n/2);
        return y*y;
    } else {
        int y = power_2(x, n/2);
        return y*y*x; 
    }
}
double power_3 (double x, int n) {
    if (n == 0){
        return 1;
    } else if (n % 2 == 0) {
        return power_3(x, n/2) * power_3(x, n/2); 
    } else {
     return power_3(x, n/2) * power_3(x, n/2) * x; 
    }
}






